Mobiles.LongDescription: Noticeable only by their badge of office, a WeinCloudstan guard patrols alertly.
Mobiles.Description: Posture strictly erect, with the native grace of one born and trained inbattle, this Cloud Giant moves with familiarity around the city.  Clad inapparel not uncommon to normal citizens, the only indication that this Giantis anything other than a Cloud Giant adventurer is the small, elaborate pinpin on their cloak, shaped in the sigil of Weincloudstan.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A WeinCloudstan Guard wanders about, keeping an eye on things.
Mobiles.Description: Sworn to defend the city from the elements considered less desirable bylaw abiding citizens, this Cloud Giant conscientiously patrols and keepsalert for any possible trouble.  While the guard's boots are spit polishedand a crease remains in the neatly pressed uniform trousers, there is acertain stiffness to the way that the guard holds themself, perhaps from anold wound.

Mobiles.LongDescription: In a hurry, a merchant barrels through.
Mobiles.Description: Intent on getting places fast, and monomaniacally aware of the importanceof their role in their own little world, this merchant moves mercilesslythrough any crowd.  Garments too rich for a common citizen, but too simplefor nobility flap in the wake of their passage.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A citizen of WeinCloudstan is probably on his way to work.
Mobiles.Description: Less well-dressed than the merchants, this citizen of the WeinCloudStanis still well dressed in business attire.  His large, attractive face wearsan expression of stress, at odds with the calmness one would expect of agiant.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A local woman walks hurriedly to accomplish her tasks.
Wendry is here organizing her vegetables.
Mobiles.Description: Short and thin by Cloud Giant standards, Wendry has devoted her life toher shop and trying to squeeze out a profit.  Her blue hair, greying now, isneatly tucked up into a few braids that loop around the top of her head, andher dress is plain to an extreme, with only a long white apron to give itany color.

Mobiles.LongDescription: As he chops some meat, Bacht whistles softly, off-key.
Mobiles.Description: A blood-spattered white apron, oddly embroidered with little flowers andlambs, encircles the waist of this stoutly built Cloud Giant.  Bachtwhistles while he works, happily and efficiently reducing corpses towell-sliced cuts of meat.  His assistants scurry around the shop about theirduties, as if unused to their master's good mood.

Mobiles.LongDescription: Although busy making sandwiches, Delli smiles at you.
Mobiles.Description: A friendly, outgoing woman, Delli is a bit heavier than the average CloudGiant, but she wears it well.  She handles the crowds in her popular shopwith ease, greeting each one with a smile.  Her good cheer has held up eventhough crowd size increased with a recent drop in prices.  Oddly enough, theprice drop occurred when she began to be seen around the city in the companyof Bacht the butcher.

Mobiles.LongDescription: Arndt pays no attention to anyone in his shop, leaving that task to his nervous apprentice.
Mobiles.Description: A tall, muscular Cloud Giant, Arndt glowers over his anvil as he works.The beat of his hammer on his anvil is steady, uninterrupted even whensomeone attempts to speak to the truculent blacksmith.  A silent apprenticewatches the fire to ensure an even heat is possible, leaving only to sell anitem or two.  The quality of the workmanship, and the expert way that Arndtdoes his job make up for the lack of welcome.

Mobiles.LongDescription: Flitc is here putting on a show for his spectators.
Mobiles.Description: Known for his charismatic flair as much as for his undisputed skill as anarmorer, Flitc is both merchant and tourist attraction.  The garments theattractive Cloud Giant wears are brightly colored, and the tough apron heworks in seems woven from storm clouds, dark and powerful.  Although Flitcseems open and willing enough to perform for the masses, he hides certainparts of his cloud-weaving, a tradition handed down in his family forgenerations.

Mobiles.LongDescription: Clyde, the executioner, is here cracking his whip.
Mobiles.Description: A big, burly Cloud Giant, Clyde's countenance is doubly marred by an eyepatch as well as the blissful, peaceful expression of a child, somehowobscene on the face of the torturer.  His whip curls familiarly in one hand,and blood spatters the brass knuckles on his other.  His head has beencompletely shaved bald of hair, leaving only a faint blue shadow against apale scalp.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A huge prison guard eyes everyone, as if deciding the cell to use.
Mobiles.Description: Guards seem to be required to be burly, but this prison guard isunusually so.  Muscles bulge beneath the fabric of his uniform, and stretchthe cloth.  The insignia of the Cloud guards is prominently displayed, and alarge club, encrusted with some dark substance, hangs from his side with aneasy familiarity.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A prisoner drenched in his own blood sleeps here.
Mobiles.Description: Dirt and bruises disguise most of the features of this prisoner.Clothings hangs off this prisoner, almost passing into the realm of rags,not that any skin is visible beneath the dirt.  Matted blue hair and straw,oily and dark, poke in odd directions from the head of the prisoner.Although unchained, hopelessness and anger emanate.

Mobiles.LongDescription: Slaransis, the Priest of WeinCloudstan, is here, deep in prayer.
Mobiles.Description: Slaransis wears flowing red robes with silver trim.  A belt of platinumwraps around his round paunch.  He spends most of his time prayingfor the sinners of WeinCloudstan.

Mobiles.LongDescription: Ernie hums and plays another hand of cards.
Mobiles.Description: A short, slim human in a city of Cloud Giants, Ernie has somehow managedto carve out his place in society.  A self-proclaimed priest of Luck, he hasdressed the part in a deep, dark blue outfit, halfway between a cassock anda tunic, and resembling a dress rather closely.  A vibrant yellow sashmatches the cross-gartering on his hose, and pointy shoes with small roundballs at the top complete the outfit.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A gambler frowns over his cards.
Mobiles.Description: Other than an initial dismissive glance, this gambler is completelyabsorbed in the high stakes game he is playing against Ernie.  He looks morethan a little desperate, sweat beading his brow, despite the fact that as aCloud Giant, he is much larger and stronger than the other player.

Mobiles.LongDescription: Butch, the kingpin of the Underworld, growls at you.
Mobiles.Description: Butch is tall and massive in build.  He is constantly growlingabout something or another.  Everyone who has been incontact with him has learned not to cross him.  At his waistyou see a huge axe connected to a ring.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A criminal eyes you suspiciously.
Mobiles.Description: This person has spent their life in the pursuit of crime.  It reallyshows, in manner and in appearance.  Their eyes constantly scan for victimsor meaner predators, and they are poised for flight (or battle) at alltimes.  All in all, certainly a character of which to be wary.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A youthful Cloud Giant wanders along, a parcel forgotten in his hand.
Mobiles.Description: Although almost the size of the adult Cloud Giants, the gangly appearanceof this young man indicates he has yet to attain his full growth.  Blue hairis somewhat disheveled above a face still round with childhood, but thefaintest shadow of blue stubble (no doubt carefully pampered to seem moremature) has begun to appear.  Usually slumping, he stands up straight onlywhen a pretty girl or authority figure appears.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A tortured man is here writhing in agony.
Mobiles.Description: Huge cuts bleed all over this poor man's body, crisscrossed with burnmarks.  Only stumps remain where his fingers once were, and only his sizedemarcates him as having been a Cloud Giant.  He makes no sounds, hisconsciousness already fled his body, as the last bits of life seep out ofhim.

Mobiles.LongDescription: Tavst the bartender fills ale pitchers with a smile.
Mobiles.Description: An older Cloud Giant, Tavst works behind the bar with the energy of amuch younger man.  Rumor has it that Tavst has very little blood left in hisalcohol stream and that accounts for his nature, accepting of almosteverything so long as it doesn't involve bloodshed in his bar.  With Tavst,the ale is always fresh, and the smiles genuinely friendly.

Mobiles.LongDescription: Saltson stands behind the counter taking orders.
Mobiles.Description: An ambitious businessman, Saltson will buy and sell just about anythingthe he thinks will bring a profit.  As a Cloud Giant, however, he is anoddity in that he does not look like the almost uniformly attractive peopleof his city.  Short (for a Giant), and completely bald save for a smallfringe of blue hair around the very base of his skull, he is also ratheroverweight, with large ears that protrude noticeably.

Mobiles.LongDescription: Franzata the jeweller is here looking at gems though a magnifying glass.
Mobiles.Description: A slim man with small, delicate hands, Franzata is an atypical CloudGiant, but very good at his job.  The careful and reverent way which hecaresses each jewel he examines, and the painstaking effort he puts intoeach creation show that it may be more of a vocation than anything else.Fitting, really, for the latest scion in a long line of Franzatta jewelers.

Mobiles.LongDescription: Fernadot mutters to himself as he adds a stitch.
Mobiles.Description: Dapperly dressed in a sharp doublet with matching hose, the tailor eyesall customers with a critical eye.  A cravat, tied so high that it is awonder he can breathe, comes up to just under his chin.  A tailor's measureis draped over his shoulders as if it were the latest in fashionaccessories, and he is almost constantly busy with alterations.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A young tough, arms crossed, eyes everyone suspiciously.
Mobiles.Description: Clad in a simple tunic and hosen outfit, this young Cloud Giant staresaggressively into the eyes of anyone and everyone, silently daring them tostart a fight.  Pouches encircle the waist of the youth, some flat andempty, others bulging with items.  The soft, silent cloth shoes of a citynative muffle the young tough's footfalls.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A girl dressed in tattered clothing hawks fresh, roasted nuts.
Mobiles.Description: Old eyes look out from a youthful face as the street vendor returns yourgaze.  Although her clothing is somewhat tattered and frayed, she'scarefully assembled the rags to cover everything that might get her chasedout of the nicer areas of town.  She carries a bag, from which steam and thepleasant nutty scent of hot roasted nuts arises.  Her voice rises and fallsin a regular rhythm as she hawks her wares.

Mobiles.LongDescription: Wide-eyed, a little girl stares at everything curiously.
Mobiles.Description: Big eyes gaze around silently beneath neatly braided blue hair.  Theotherwise tidy little dress she is wearing falls modestly to just above herankles, with a suspicious stain on one sleeve where it dipped into somethingthat the child had reached for.  A doll, more treasured than valuable, isclutched tightly in one arm.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A girl checks her hair self-consciously as she walks along.
Mobiles.Description: The young face of a girl anxiously awaiting adulthood has been carefullymade up to make her seem more mature than her actual age.  Ruthlessly, herblue hair has been stylized into an ornate collection of curls, ringlets,and bows, in a unique hairstyle seen in no one but other girls her age.  Herfrock is a tad too short for propriety, but she appears, overall, happyenough.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A little boy curiously pokes at things with his finger.
Very seriously, the teacher explains the role of a citizen.
Mobiles.Description: Soberly dressed in a patriotic uniform of blue and white, not unlike thatof the Palace guards, the teacher has a thoughtful expression at all times.Gentle in habit and demeanor, the absolute sobriety with which the teacherapproached the task of educating the children is indicative of theimportance placed on their role in society.

Mobiles.LongDescription: A burly guard watches everyone with a bored look.
Mobiles.Description: Dressed in the uniform of the Palace Guards, this guard has beenassigned, perhaps as a punishment, the duty of observing that everyonefollows governmental restrictions when in official buildings.  From theglazed look in the guard's eyes, any sort of disruption would be a welcomerelief from the boredom of this job, particularly if it involved violence.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `lA bright blue pigeon flutters around, looking for food.``
Mobiles.Description: Large, fat, and with a mean look in its eyes, this pigeon is out for foodand to defecate on expensive things and public statuary.  Bright blue, andmuch larger than its more earthbound companion below, the Cloud Pigeon roamsthe streets, ceaselessly seeking food.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `lA large, winged blue sheep feeds placidly, ignoring the attached cart.``
Mobiles.Description: Baaaa.  It's a blue sheep, about the size of an elephant, with wingsincredibly long and powerful, but that fold along its body when not in use.Someone has hooked up a harness and a cart to it, and a few stray pieces ofgrain spill out the back of the cart.  The cargo is otherwise completelygone.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `lA bright blue robe bustles around the shop, its occupant invisible.``
Mobiles.Description: The person within these robes is completely and totally invisible.Judging from the telltale way the robe falls over his invisible frame, theshopkeeper is a Cloud Giant, around shorter than average height, and on thethin side.  Spectacles hover in midair above the robe, probably sitting onhis nose.  "Sorry," the robe says, "I was trying this new spell and itdidn't quite work right but next time it might.  It's only been a fewdecades, you know."

Mobiles.LongDescription: An elderly man haragues younger Giants raucously.
Mobiles.Description: In the hair completely white with age, and wrinkles at the corners of hiseyes and mouth, this elderly Cloud Giant shows his age.  Although hisshoulders are stooped and his stomach a bit rounded, his voice is loud andvigorous as he haragues anyone younger than himself about the profligate andflighty ways of the younger generations.  In his day, things were different,oh yes.

Mobiles.LongDescription: `nThe ancient Titan, `lKronus `nguards here.``
Mobiles.Description: `nKronus is the final link to `lW`nein`lC`nloudstan ancestory. A Titan, the ancestor of the cloud giants.He towers over the colossal giants, wearing reminders of a troubled past spent defending his people.``

Rooms.RoomDescription: An enormous gate, unmoving granite chased with designs in platinum andgold rises from the clouds, reaching still higher upwards.  The emblem of agold cloud with a lightning bolt emerging from it, in platinum, is visiblein the center of the door when the gates are closed.  The tip of a mountainpokes through the clouds below, and a large, oddly flattened cloud is to thesouth.

Under the shadow cast by the massive City gates to the south, this streetis made of cobblestone, set farther apart than most humans and demi-humansare used to, even too far apart for a half-ogre to feel comfortable.  To thenorth, you can see an enormous blue funnel, siphoning clouds into a pool ofwater in Imperial Circle.  East and west, farmers load grain, vegetables,and other foodstuffs into large warehouses.  A small sign has been postedhere.

The main commercial intersection for the city, Imperial Circle marks theintersection of Empress Avenue, running north to south, and Market Way,running east to west.  The tall, inlaid gates to the city are visible to thesouth, as well as farmers carrying in food to the warehouses.  Northwards,the ornate gates to the imperial castle are just barely visible.

During the busier hours of the day, the noise of the bustling life of thecity is almost overwhelming, especially with Imperial Circle, the maincommercial intersection, to the south.  Empress Avenue continues northwards,towards the looming Palace gates.  Small homes, and businesses dot eitherside of this thoroughfare.

The cobblestone street of Empress Avenue continues north and south.  Theornate Palace gates loom over the circle that bears that domicile's name tothe north.  On either side of the road, small businesses go about theirdaily work.  In a glimpse in one window, rows of Cloud Giant women sewindustriously.

To the north, the Imperial Palace gates loom overhead, solid masses ofsmooth stone, with the blue and white flag of WeinCloudstan flying aboveeach tower on the gate.  The faint shimmer of armor in the twin towers ofthe gate mark the presence of guards.  Olde Castle Way runs to the west, theglinting golden dome of the Cloude Duomo just visible above the crowdedbuildings of the street.  Veccicho Bridge, a beautiful work of art soaringthrough the air to connect to some of the more exclusive shops in the cityis to the east.

Market Way bustles with commerce most of the time, pedestrians sometimesshoulder to shoulder as they shop or pass through on their way to work.Fresh vegetables in the grocer shop to the north, labelled 'Wendry's VeggieDelight' tempt passers to stop for a snack.  The eloquently simple signshaped like a butcher's knife almost does not need the lettering proclaimingit "Bacht's Butchery' to describe its products.

During the day, this section of the street is so crowded that people mustpush their way through the crowds or risk never attaining theirdestinations.  Smaller races, such as humans or dwarves, practically have towear a helmet to protect them from being stepped on, and must moveespecially quickly.  Cloude Street leads to the north, and the Corner StoneTrading Post is to the South.

Market Way ends in this quiet little cul-de-sac.  Small buildings lineall sides of it, with the faintly subdued clatter of industrious work justbarely audible beneath the regular noise of the street.  Eastwards, MarketWay passes through the commercial district of the city, and the signs ofvarious businesses protrude from streetfronts.

Huge slices of various types of meat hang from the ceiling.  You cansmell the aroma of fresh sausages and raw meat.  Bacht and his assistantsare always open and guarantee satisfaction with their products.

This well-kept cobblestone street is rarely quiet, with people movingabout even at night upon it.  Southwards, a hanging sign indicates a foodplace, Delli's Cloud Deli, complete with a picture of a loaf of breadunderneath for those who cannot read.  Market Way continues to the east andwest, with the water funnel of Imperial Circle just visible to the west.

Market Way continues, to the east meeting South Stormy Street.  A smithystands to the south, metal coiled into the letters naming it as `iArndt'sSmithy`n, painted tidily in red.  The display items, behind an iron grill,seem to include more weapons than horseshoes or farming implements.  At mosttimes, people crowd this section of the street, going about their dailybusiness, or just enjoying the sights and sounds of this part of the city.

Market Way and Stormy Street join in this cul-de-sac in a smooth curve,as a residential district and the business district intersect.  Southwards,a brilliantly shined breastplate in the window has 'The Armory of Flitc'enscribed in elaborate scrollwork all over it.

Always crowded, the deli bustles with life.  A few chairs and tables arescattered throughout the room, but there never seem to be enough for all thepeople that gather here.  A long wooden counter separates Delli's workspacefrom her customers, with meats and cheeses along the wall behind her,visible to all.  A fresh bouquet of flowers stand in an inexpensive vase onthe end of one counter, far enough from the edge and maddening crowds toavoid being knocked over.

Rooms.EnterMsg: Arndt grunts to his apprentice as $n enters.
Rooms.ExitMsg: The apprentice blacksmith relaxes a little as $n exits.
Rooms.RoomDescription: Weapons of excellent caliber decorate the most of the walls of the shop,save for the one claimed by a wide stone hearth and roaring fire, where theblacksmith plies his trade.  Here and there, pots, horseshoes, and the likeare tossed among the weapons with an indifference visible even to the casualobserver.  Heat from the fire fills the room, raising the ambianttemperature considerably.

An enormous loom, with gleaming, metallic strands of cloud material, spuninto threads by an unknown process, fills one side of this room.  On apadded bench next to the loom, the armorer can usually be found plying histrade.  A window to the north looks out onto Market Way and Stormy Street,allowing him moments of diversion from his task.  A well-polishedbreastplate in the window is, to the touch, incredibly thin and fragile,while the other items displayed for sale seem quite sturdy, despite thegossamer fabric from which they were created.

A neighborhood of the less prosperous merchants and artisans, SouthStormy Street is neither poor nor wealthy.  Residents have enough money toown their own homes and a few nice things, but none of the opulence visiblein the homes of nobles or more affluent merchants.  Near the commercialdistrict, residents rarely have to go far to get anything they need.

Once the main thoroughfare for the city before being replaced by EmpressAvenue, Olde Castle Way retains very few of the shops that used to line thestreet.  Eastwards, Palace Circle bustles with activity, quite the contrastto the largely silent buildings here.  The brick facades that replaced theshops are slightly crumbly with age, but have been well-maintained and nowseem to house small businesses that manufacture items like saddle bucklesand kitchen implements.

Ancient cobblestones wobble slightly underfoot.  The walls of the Palacerise high impressively to the north, towering over the older brick buildingsthat lean against it.  The glittering dome of the Duomo is visible westwardsat all hours, courtesy of the holy lights that illuminate it when the sunhas gone down.  Southwards, a creaky building houses a shop with a glowingsign reading `iOutre `lOddities.  ``

Olde Castle Way is an ancient road, the remnant of a bygone era, nowtravelled only by those wishing to view the remains of the past.  To thewest, the Cloude Duomo towers.  Made of white and green marble in acheckered pattern, the Duomo stands hundreds of feet high and is topped by ahuge golden dome.

Northwards, the jagged and lonely ruins of the old castle, replaced bythe resplendent Palace of the current imperial family, stand alone.Buildings one or two stories in height, slightly run down, stand to the eastand west.  While occasionally cobbles wobble underfoot, this section of theroad has been patched recently.

Rooms.RoomName: The end of Olde Castle Way
Rooms.RoomDescription: From this vantage point, a nearby cloud is visible with the remains of anold castle.  Large, jagged stone fragments slash upwards in those placeswhere the walls have not crumbled completely, and stony gargoyles, all themore grotesque for missing wings, eyes, and other portions, leer from wherethey have fallen.  Around the edge of the cloud, someone has constructed asturdy fence to keep people from falling off the cloud.

This is the lobby of an enormous, multi-story building, with rooms rentedon a semi-permanent basis to the busy Giants of the city.  Functionalbenches and tables are scattered throughout the room, allowing people tovisit if necessary.  A small sign states that visitors are not allowed inthe boarding house rooms except with dispensation from the housekeeper.

This is the lobby of an enormous, multi-story building, with rooms rentedon a semi-permanent basis to the busy Giants of the city.  Rough, worn,benches and tables are scattered throughout the room, allowing people tovisit if necessary.  A small sign states that visitors are not allowed inthe boarding house rooms except with dispensation from the housekeeper.

Rooms.RoomName: Cloude Street and West Market Way
Rooms.RoomDescription: In this busy corner of the city, Cloude Street and West Market Wayintersect.  Westwards, Cloude Street leads through the main residentialdistrict of the WeinCloudstan.  Cloude Street ends here, in front of anotherboarding house, while West Market Way begins and leads southwards to thebusiness district.

As with most places in the city, this section of the street bustles withactivity at all hours.  To the south, a huge house, several stories high,has a scroll in the window advertising rooms to let.  Eastwards, CloudeStreet and West Market Way intersect in an almost dizzying flurry ofactivity.

A mix of old and new homes, Cloude Street continues to the east andnorth.  While some of the homes show a bit of neglect, still others havebeen scrupulously maintained.  South and north, two large, stately old homeshave been converted to boarding houses, though both have small signs in thewindows indicating no rooms are currently available.

This is the lobby of an enormous, multi-story building, with rooms rentedon a semi-permanent basis to the busy Giants of the city.  Functionalbenches and tables are scattered throughout the room, allowing people tovisit if necessary.  A small sign states that visitors are not allowed inthe boarding house rooms except with dispensation from the housekeeper.

Cloud Street calms into a small cul-de-sac, the bustling press of thestreets further south lessened here.  To the west, a large house sprawlsout, a small sign marking it as the WeinCloudstan Citizens' School.  Other,small houses surround the cul-de-sac peacefully.

This is the lobby of an enormous, multi-story building, with rooms rentedon a semi-permanent basis to the busy Giants of the city.  Functionalbenches and tables are scattered throughout the room, allowing people tovisit if necessary.  A small sign states that visitors are not allowed inthe boarding house rooms except with dispensation from the housekeeper.

The first room of the school, this classroom is crowded with desks andchairs, the perfect size for giant children.  Locked doors lead further intothe school to the west, but signs indicate admittance is limited to teachersonly.  Rows of books line the walls, with patriotic pictures of the Empressand the city the only real decoration in the room, other than desks, whichhave been painted blue and white in an alternating sequence.

Crowded with Cloud Giants during the day, at night South Stormy Streetquiets considerably.  Small homes crowd each other to the west, and asprawling house, finely carved sign somewhat chipped with age, advertises aboarding house to the east.

Although crowded in daylight hours, this area of the street shows thesmall, petty depredations of encroaching age and minor vandalism,undoubtedly performed during the darkest hours of the night.  The famedshops and view of Veccicho Bridge glint with promise to the west.  An oldmansion, shutters loose on its windows, advertises rooms to let to the east.

As the sounds and activity of the south start to fade, new sounds, thosecommon to residential areas, with the regular noises of traffic begin torise in volume.  Small homes, careworn, line both sides of the street, someimmaculately maintained, and others with paint chipping and peeling.Eastwards, a light burns in the window of one of the houses.

This section of Stormy Street is in a very poor state.  Abandonedbuildings line the sides of the streets, and the once functional cobblestonestreet is missing many stones, creating a tough to tread path.

`lShamelessly gaudy and bright, the torches burn in red lit lanterns tothe east, anouncing the presence of the "`qCasino WeinCloudstan`l" to theeast.  People walk in and out of the casino at all hours, in various moodsand states of dress, though it is common to see someone go in drunk andhappy, and be pushed out drunk and unhappy.  ``

At the foot of the bridge, two elegant shops face each other and look outover the impressive view.  Jewels glimmer in striking patterns, protectedfrom theft in the windows of the northern shop, visible even through thegrill pattern over the window.  To the south, the light glimmers off goldenthread in an exquisitely embroidered vest.  Discreet signs invite shoppersto enter.  To the east, Stormy Street runs north and south.

A largely empty room with a white, cloud rug on the floor and a fewscattered pins, this tailor shop hides the majority of the inventory and thestock in the back, where customers cannot trespass.  A large mirror coversone wall, and the opposite wall striped with brilliant colors and fabrics asbolts of cloth have been stored there.

Magical lights, brilliantly white, are positioned carefully to displaythe glittering jewels within the glass cases within this shop.  Every casehums softly with magic, and a sweet floral scent is in the air.  A fewcarefully framed scrolls proclaim the long and proud history of this shop,and the excellence of the quality of jewels here, signed by the mark of theEmpress herself.

This is the lobby of an enormous, multi-story building, with rooms rentedon a semi-permanent basis to the busy Giants of the city.  Functionalbenches and tables are scattered throughout the room, allowing people tovisit if necessary.  A battered sign states that visitors are not allowed inthe boarding house rooms without the owner's permission.  The floor isdusty, and the staircase up, once with a finely carved banister, leansdangerously to the right.

This is the lobby of an enormous, multi-story building, with rooms rentedon a semi-permanent basis to the busy Giants of the city.  Functionalbenches and tables are scattered throughout the room, allowing people tovisit if necessary.  A small sign states that visitors are not allowed inthe boarding house rooms except with dispensation from the housekeeper.

A single room, by virtue of a few ropes, is curtained into sections.  Asimple pallet lies on the floor behind one curtain.  Behind the othercurtain, a simple chamber pot and basin of water resides, along with a largemetal tub.  The main room of the chamber includes a table, some chairs, anda simple, worn rug.  The fireplace is dark and cold as the inhabitants arenot home.

People, mostly Cloud Giants, laugh a bit too loudly as they clusteraround tables and make their bets.  One small area in the corner of the roomseems to be roped off for mouse races, while another seems devoted toserving liquor of the hardest kind and parting people from their money asfast as possible.

Numerous roulette, blackjack, and craps tables litter this floor of thecasino, with stairs leading down.  The drone of drunken voices almost drownsout the constant shuffle of cards, rattle of dice, and whirr spin ofroulette wheels.  Laughter here has the sound of people who have imbibed toomany alcoholic drinks.  Guards keep a cautious eye on the tables as well asa seemingly empty area of the room.

A single table surrounded by chairs stands in the center of this smallroom, walls lavishly decorated with tapestries depicting erotic conquests,and floor covered with a deep, colorful woven rug that could only have comefrom the City of the Sun.  Pure white beeswax candles burn in gilded candleholders, and the scent of rich tobacco hangs heavily in the air.

This part of the city looks very run down.  At one time it was the centerof everything, however, now there is a serious crime problem.  The west isblocked by the thick, forbidding wall of the prison, and an old house isslowing eroding to the east.  Southwards, a burst of noise and lightsannounces the one successful business in this area.

Showing signs of age and abuse, this part of the city has been run downby wear and neglect.  Once the center of everything, now a prison has beenbuilt to the west, replacing whatever ediface used to stand there.  Thosethat pass tend to wear poorer clothes, and be less cheerfully rushed thanthose in more affluent areas of the city.

This part of the city looks very run down.  At one time it was the centerof everything, however, now there is a serious crime problem.  The burntshell of a building moulders to the east, with dark shadows too indistinctto identify moving behind it.  Stormy Street continues north and south.

This part of the city looks very run down.  At one time it was the centerof everything, however, now there is a serious crime problem here.  Bothnewcomers and regulars are eyed with suspicion.  To the east and west,houses have been burned almost to the ground.  The end of Stormy Street isto the north, and it continues to the south.

While obviously this was once the center of the city, based on the wear,this area has fallen into a state of disreputable retirement.  It is worn,run-down, and corrupted by rot.  Many of the local Cloud Giants here mirrorthe area: disreputable and corrupt.  Newcomers are regarded with suspicionor as likely targets.  A few buildings have crumbled or been destroyed.  Thesoot-blackened remains of a building slowly moulder to the east.

Charred wood, metal, and other unidentifiable objects litter the groundhere.  A thick layer of black ash and soot, long cold, blankets everything,even a warped remnant of a sign saying R S for LE.  Discarded bits of trashlie here and there, completing the desolation.

A thick layer of black ash and soot, long cold, blankets everything.Discarded bits of trash lie here and there, completing the desolation.  Amidall this, a shack, thrown together out of boards still bearing the scorchmarks of the fire that ravaged this area, looks about ready to tumble downand contains nothing particularly of value, just a smelly, grimy pallet.

Rooms.EnterMsg: Reaching through the bars, a drunk mistakenly greets $n as his mother.
Rooms.ExitMsg: A chorus of catcalls and hoots follow $n out.
Rooms.RoomDescription: A spartan office with unwelcoming benches set here and there for theconvenience of giving visitors splinters, the main lobby of theWeinCloudstan Prison makes no pretense at being anything other than what itis.  The foul scent of urine, sweat, and fear almost manage to mask thescent of blood.  The heavy doors eastwards that lead to the streets andfreedom are left unlocked.  Westwards, a large cell holds what look likeminor offenders, drunks and the like.  Faint screams drift up a stairwayleading down.

Rudimentary pallets of straw, soiled, are heaped up around the walls ofthis large, dark room.  A table, bolted into the wall, allows the prisonersto stand and eat the pitiful meals that this prison offers.  A nasty wordhas been scratched into the wall here by one of the prisoners.

The scent of blood is overwhelming in the closed confines of this room.A large rack, encrusted with the dark remains of previous victims, takescenter stage in the room, with many whips, knives, and other instruments oftorture hanging all over the walls.  Beneath the rack, a circular groove inthe floor channels any blood into a hole.  An enormous iron maiden takes upone corner of the room, with eye holes cut out so the victim may stareacross at the cell of prisoners to the west.

`aDark , dank, and disgusting, a small room holds major offendersmanacled to the walls when they are not enduring the gentle ministrations ofthe torturer.  The cell door and the iron manacles are the only things thatlook well made.  A `bwindow`a, barred, allows occupants to catch glimpses ofanything going on in the torture chamber.

Once the basement of one of the houses that burned down, this room nowserves as a headquarters for crime in WeinCloudstan.  It has been simplyfurnished, but the furniture is of solid manufacture, and though worn,testifies to the prosperity of the Cloud Giant underworld.  The sheersparsity of the room also states that this is little more than a meetingroom - no one would live here.  A large chair sits at the head of the table,cleverly mimicing the throne of the Empress.

The duomo is an enormous dome, open at the center, allowing a steady beamof light in, day and night, and decorated with a delicated gold and platinumleaf mosaic.  The gods of the Cloud Giants are displayed in the brilliantgold and platinum.  An altar is directly under the center of the dome, andduring high noon a beam of light illuminates the priest while he preaches.

Battered rugs unravel down the hallway.  While the walls have beenpainted blue, time and light from outside have aged and striped the paint,so that it peels and the color is uneven.  Simple doors, numbers painted inwhite, line the sides of the long hallway in this tired boarding house.

Both historic and functional, this bridge has stood for centuries, andarcs across a gap in the clouds, joining Empress Avenue and Stormy Street.Carefully inspected and renewed every few decades, the bridge never moveseven under the heaviest of carts.  A thick rail of the sturdy cloud materialused for Cloud Giant armor prevents anyone from falling from the bridge.Below, the tips of mountains blur into lower clouds, and birds soar below ina dazzling view of the world and lower-lying clouds.

Rooms.EnterMsg: The guard booms, "Please place your documents on the desk and go. You will be notified when completed or if any changes are necessary."
Rooms.ExitMsg: The guard loses interest in $name as soon as $e steps out the door.
Rooms.RoomDescription: The foyer of this building has a small desk with an impressively muscledCloud Giant behind it.  Through a window in the doors to the east and south,one or two blue heads can be seen passing by quickly.  The soft rumble ofvoices from behind the doors indicates the probability of many more unseenCloud Giants in the building.  A small sign on the desk says "Paperworkhere."

This cloud has been appended to the larger cloud upon which WeinCloudstansits.  Curiously flattened, it is also dotted with large piles of an unknownsubstance which rather smells.  A few simple posts are here and there,suitable for tying up animals, but very little else is here.

Noise from the common room below echoes up the stairs and into this smallhallway.  A long rug, woven of the ubiquitous cloud material, runs thelength of the hall.  While the walls have been painted a cheerful blue, theonly decorations are the doors to the rooms, each painted a different color.

Sparsely furnished, this room is large enough for perhaps four CloudGiants to stand in at once.  Northwards, a small window looks out over thecity, the opulence of the Imperial Palace just barely visible.  A small bedlines one wall, and a table holds a basin against the other wall.  The onlysplash of color in the all-white room is an inexpensive vase holding someyellow flowers.

Sparsely furnished, this room is large enough for perhaps four CloudGiants to stand in at once.  A large bed lines one wall, and a table holds abasin against the other wall.  The only splash of color in the all-blue roomis an inexpensive vase holding some yellow flowers.  The door is a darkershade of blue against the pale blue walls.

Rooms.EnterMsg: A gargoyle's eyes light up, and he peeps like a chick.
Rooms.ExitMsg: A gargoyle's eyes light up and he clucks like a chicken.
Rooms.RoomDescription: A dark room, filled with numerous items that are odd at best, this littleshop seems to try to live up to its name.  On either side of of the door, agargoyle leers at all who enter.  One wears a flamboyant pink beret and theother sports checkered leggings.  Oddly enough, the shop smells likecinnamon and apples, possibly from the dried plants arrayed in a stonepixie's arms on one wall.

Rooms.EnterMsg: A cow bell clangs as $n enters.
Rooms.ExitMsg: The clang of a cheap cow bell sounds as $n exits.
Rooms.RoomDescription: Severely plain, this store is nonetheless well-kept.  Vegetables areneatly piled in several bins about the shop, freshly scrubbed and recentlypicked, judging from the lack of rot visible.  A counter is set up by thewindow, allowing the shopkeeper to watch the busy inhabitants of the citypassing by on their daily business.

Rooms.EnterMsg: Saltson says cheerfully, "Greetings, $name, how may I help you today?"
Rooms.ExitMsg: Saltson waves and booms after the departing customer, "Come again soon!"
Rooms.RoomDescription: Crowded with an astonishing multiplicity of items, this trading postseems to offer a variety stunning in its lack of coherent purpose.  Lightstumble over weapons and armor, propped up by unassuming wands and stavesthat spark gently with suppressed magic.  A long counter runs the back ofthe room, where the storekeeper usually waits for his next customer.

Rooms.EnterMsg: The Innkeeper, Tavst, nods to $n in greeting.
Rooms.ExitMsg: Tavst wishes $n a good journey as $e departs.
Rooms.RoomDescription: A WeinCloudstan landmark, the Cloude Tavern has stood for centuries inthis spot.  Comfortable tables and chairs of all sizes and shapes, thoughpredominately meant for Cloud Giants, are scattered throughout the room,with a few benches along the wall by the fireplace.
